Based on the statistical analyses of the match and odd information, we try to infer information about behaviours of odds. Before doing calculations, we must prepare the data that we are given.

In this task, we try to understand if bookmakers are good at deciding over/under 2.5 odds. Mainly, the data we are going to focus on is the one with totalhandicap=2.5 and betType=ou.

odd_rawdata_ <- odd_rawdata[betType == "ou" & totalhandicap == 
    2.5]

odd_rawdata_[, `:=`(row_number, rank(odd_date)), by = c("bookmaker",

odd_over_under_final <- odd_rawdata_[row_number == "1"]

We are asked to select 5 bookmakers and plot the implied “over” probability average in a bin versus the fraction of games finished over for the corresponding bin.We can filter our data for each bookmaker.Betway is selected for illustration purposes.

# get bookmaker's initial over under odds

In order to reach match results in the odd data, we should merge these two data.

# join odds with matches
merged_matches_fraction = merge(bookmaker, matches_rawdata_,

Also, we should normalize the probabilities since they are not summed up to 1 due to bookmaker margin.

# normalize

merged_matches_fraction[, `:=`(probUnder, probUnder/totalProb)]

Betway cannot be considered as successful bookmaker for low and high bins since the points look far away from the x=y line. However, in the middle, there are some correct guesses between 0.4 and 0.6 bins. In the final odd plot, the points are closer to the x=y line. Hence, the final bets for match results are better to guess the score.As you can see,the points(bins) are scattered for each year. Therefore, we do not whether Betway is successful for all the time in the middle bins.

We can do the same steps for remaining the 4 bookmakers such as bet365,William Hill,Unibet and bwin.

Scatter Plot of Initial Odds

# bookmakers
x_bookmaker = c("bet365", "William Hill", "Unibet", "bwin")
for (i in 1:4) {
    bookmaker_over_under = odd_over_under_initial[bookmaker == 
        x_bookmaker[i]]
    
    bookmaker = dcast(bookmaker_over_under, matchId ~ oddtype, 
        value.var = "odd")
    
    # join odds with matches
    merged_matches_fraction = merge(bookmaker, matches_rawdata_, 
        by = "matchId")
    
    # normalize
    merged_matches_fraction[, `:=`(probOver, 1/over)]
    merged_matches_fraction[, `:=`(probUnder, 1/under)]
    merged_matches_fraction[, `:=`(totalProb, probOver + probUnder)]
    
    merged_matches_fraction[, `:=`(probOver, probOver/totalProb)]
    merged_matches_fraction[, `:=`(probUnder, probUnder/totalProb)]
    
    # bins
    cutpoints = c(0, 0.05, 0.1, 0.15, 0.45, 0.5, 0.55, 0.6, 0.65, 
        0.8, 0.85, 0.9, 0.95, 1)
    merged_matches_fraction[, `:=`(bins, cut(probOver, cutpoints))]
    years = t(sapply(merged_matches_fraction$match_date, function(x) substring(x, 
        first = c(1, 2, 3, 4), last = c(1, 2, 3, 4))))
    merged_matches_fraction[, "years"] <- paste0(years[, 1], 
        years[, 2], years[, 3], years[, 4])
    
    # lets look at the results
    result = merged_matches_fraction[, list(fraction_over_games = mean(as.numeric(over_flag)), 
        over_prob_average_ = mean(probOver), .N), by = list(bins, 
        years)]
    result = result[order(bins)]
    
    # plot
    plot(over_prob_average_ ~ fraction_over_games, pch = 20, 
        cex = 1.5, col = "red", data = result, xlim = c(0, 1), 
        ylim = c(0, 1), xlab = "Fraction of over games", ylab = "Over Probability Average", 
        main = paste("Scatter Plot of", x_bookmaker[i], "for inital odd"))
    # text(over_prob_average_~fraction_over_games,labels=bins,data=result,
    # adj=c(1.2,0),cex=0.8,font=2)
    abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = "blue", lwd = 2)
}

Scatter Plot of Final Odds

# bookmakers
x_bookmaker = c("bet365", "William Hill", "Unibet", "bwin")
for (i in 1:4) {

        value.var = "odd")

    merged_matches_fraction = merge(bookmaker, matches_rawdata_, 
        by = "matchId")
    
    # normalize
    merged_matches_fraction[, `:=`(probOver, 1/over)]
    merged_matches_fraction[, `:=`(probUnder, 1/under)]
    merged_matches_fraction[, `:=`(totalProb, probOver + probUnder)]
    
    merged_matches_fraction[, `:=`(probOver, probOver/totalProb)]
    merged_matches_fraction[, `:=`(probUnder, probUnder/totalProb)]
    
    # bins
    cutpoints = c(0, 0.05, 0.1, 0.15, 0.45, 0.5, 0.55, 0.6, 0.65,

    merged_matches_fraction[, `:=`(bins, cut(probOver, cutpoints))]
    years = t(sapply(merged_matches_fraction$match_date, function(x) substring(x,

In general, the final odds given by bookmakers are better than the initial odds. If odd is too small or too high, the match result may not be occurred as proposed. Therefore, the middle probabilities (0.4-0.6) have more chance to meet the target. Interestingly, William Hill seems to be better in guessing the results with initial odds. The reason is that it may change a lot the odd values since final odds look more separated from each other. Unibet and bwin are better compared to other bookmakers. Their final odds are guessed more correctly comparing with the inital odds.

In general,the fraction of games ended as over has no significant change over years.Bwin can be considered as successfull to follow the trend. For(0.15-0.45) bin, the probabilistic over curve which is determined by bookmaker is under the empirical curve for almost all years.However,for(0.45,0.50) bin, probabilistic over curve is almost the same as fraction of over games. In the middle bins, there are small variations over the years.However, when we go further along the bins, the fractions move away from each other.

TASK 2

In this task,we try to observe the changes in the odds. We focus on the change of the odds for 1x2 bets. Also, we can choose the bookmaker as bwin again.

For visualization, I will try to create a 3D plot whose axes represent the odd types such as odd1, odd2 and oddX. In this way, we can see the all odd changes of the bookmaker in one plot. Also, I believe that change in any odd type is depending on the others. For example, if oddX is changed for a specific match, bookmaker may change the other odds such as odd1 and odd2 as well. Therefore, we should see the changes occurred by time. I think,we can see the replacement of the results in a 3D environment.

Before plotting the results, we should make some arrangements. The data that we are given includes the change in odds row by row. However, we need the current odd’s distribution in one row. In other words, suppose that bookmaker gave the odd’s values 1.5,1.35, and 1.65 for odd1,oddX and odd2 respectively. After that, the oddX is changed. Now, the odd values become 1.5,1.4, and 1.65 for odd1,oddX and odd2. Therefore, we should prepare our data in this structure.

Let’s generate the raw data.

odds_ordered = odd_rawdata[betType == "1x2" & bookmaker == "bwin"][order(matchId, 
    date)]
oddtype_data = odds_ordered[, c(1, 5, 3, 6)]
head(oddtype_data, 5)
##     matchId       date oddtype  odd
## 1: 004f4ING 1421001060    odd1 1.62
## 2: 004f4ING 1421001060    odd2 5.00
## 3: 004f4ING 1421001060    oddX 4.00
## 4: 004f4ING 1422806280    odd1 1.67
## 5: 004f4ING 1422806280    odd2 5.50

odd1, odd2 and oddX columns are generated.

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:data.table':
## 
##     between, first, last
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
oddtype_data_1 = oddtype_data %>% select(matchId, date) %>% mutate(odd1 = case_when(oddtype_data$oddtype == 
    "odd1" ~ oddtype_data$odd))

oddtype_data_2 = oddtype_data_1 %>% select(matchId, date, odd1) %>% 
    mutate(odd2 = case_when(oddtype_data$oddtype == "odd2" ~ 
        oddtype_data$odd))

oddtype_data_3 = oddtype_data_2 %>% select(matchId, date, odd1, 
    odd2) %>% mutate(oddX = case_when(oddtype_data$oddtype == 
    "oddX" ~ oddtype_data$odd))
# make NA as 0
oddtype_data_3[is.na(oddtype_data_3)] <- 0

As you can see, we have multiple rows for each match date. The 0’s in columns mean that there is no change in the odd. If there is value in the corresponding odd, then a value is associated with it.

head(oddtype_data_3, 5)
##    matchId       date odd1 odd2 oddX
## 1 004f4ING 1421001060 1.62  0.0    0
## 2 004f4ING 1421001060 0.00  5.0    0
## 3 004f4ING 1421001060 0.00  0.0    4
## 4 004f4ING 1422806280 1.67  0.0    0
## 5 004f4ING 1422806280 0.00  5.5    0

Now, we can summed up the rows for each specific matchId and date. Also, in the data, there is no 2 changes in a odd type for a specific date. Each date has a change at most 3 because of we have 3 odd types.

oddtype_data_4 = oddtype_data_3 %>% group_by(matchId, date) %>% 
    summarise(odd1 = sum(odd1), odd2 = sum(odd2), oddX = sum(oddX))

oddtype_data_4 = data.table(oddtype_data_4)

# the loops are for the zero values in the data. It basically
# replace the zero values with the older value since there is
# no change in there.

for (j in 1:length(oddtype_data_4$matchId)) {
    if (oddtype_data_4$odd1[j] == 0) {
        oddtype_data_4$odd1[j] <- oddtype_data_4$odd1[j - 1]
    } else oddtype_data_4$odd1[j] <- oddtype_data_4$odd1[j]
}


for (j in 1:length(oddtype_data_4$matchId)) {
    if (oddtype_data_4$odd2[j] == 0) {
        oddtype_data_4$odd2[j] <- oddtype_data_4$odd2[j - 1]
    } else oddtype_data_4$odd2[j] <- oddtype_data_4$odd2[j]
}

for (j in 1:length(oddtype_data_4$matchId)) {
    if (oddtype_data_4$oddX[j] == 0) {
        oddtype_data_4$oddX[j] <- oddtype_data_4$oddX[j - 1]
    } else oddtype_data_4$oddX[j] <- oddtype_data_4$oddX[j]
}

After summing, we can see the odd values for each time. When a value of oddtype is changed, the date and new odd values are given under that row.

As you can see, there is a V shape in the corner of odd1 and oddX. Most of the odds are changed in that region. Also, there are some variations between odds since some points looks far away from each other.

In order to see the changes clearly, we can look the difference between initial and final odd values of each odd type for each matchID.Therefore, we can see how difference is distributed.

oddtype_data_4[, `:=`(row_number, rank(date)), by = c("matchId")]  #for initial odds
oddtype_initial <- oddtype_data_4[row_number == "1"]

oddtype_data_4[, `:=`(row_number, rank(-date)), by = c("matchId")]  #for final odds
oddtype_final <- oddtype_data_4[row_number == "1"]

oddtype_initial = oddtype_initial[, c(1, 3, 4, 5)]
oddtype_final = oddtype_final[, c(1, 3, 4, 5)]
merged_oddtype = merge(oddtype_final, oddtype_initial, by = "matchId")  ##change

merged_oddtype[, "odd1_difference"] <- merged_oddtype[, 2] - 
    merged_oddtype[, 5]
merged_oddtype[, "odd2_difference"] <- merged_oddtype[, 3] - 
    merged_oddtype[, 6]
merged_oddtype[, "oddX_difference"] <- merged_oddtype[, 4] - 
    merged_oddtype[, 7]

oddtype_final_difference = merged_oddtype[, c(1, 8, 9, 10)]
